    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2138969456" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2138969456" />
    <a title="Eileen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/55389776-eileen"><img alt="Eileen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591636449p2/55389776.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2138969456?book_show_action=true">Oct 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eileen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eileen" href="/user/show/55389776-eileen">Eileen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781609751395" href="/book/show/31338484-the-sailweaver-s-son">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/55389776-eileen?shelf=rochester">rochester</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/55389776-eileen?shelf=library-books">library-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/55389776-eileen?shelf=scifi-and-fantasy">scifi-and-fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/55389776-eileen?shelf=usa">usa</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2138969456" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8499794570722910410"><i>The Sailweaver&apos;s Son</i> is first in a YA steampunk fantasy series set in an alternate world called Etherium, where humans live high in the mountains and travel in airships due to an unusually dense atmosphere. There are also dragons, flying jellyfish, and wizards who live on floating islands. The lower regions are inhabited by a humanoid race known as the Gublins, who are held in fear and suspicion by the human kingdoms for their alleged habit of eating children. <br/><br/>15-year-old Tak is the son of a hig</span>
  <span id="freeText8499794570722910410" style="display:none"><i>The Sailweaver's Son</i> is first in a YA steampunk fantasy series set in an alternate world called Etherium, where humans live high in the mountains and travel in airships due to an unusually dense atmosphere. There are also dragons, flying jellyfish, and wizards who live on floating islands. The lower regions are inhabited by a humanoid race known as the Gublins, who are held in fear and suspicion by the human kingdoms for their alleged habit of eating children. <br /><br />15-year-old Tak is the son of a high-ranking sailweaver and spends his time irritating palace defenses by swooping in too close on his personal aircraft, the <i>Arrow</i>. One day, however, he witnesses a mysterious bubble rise from the depths below and destroy a royal battleship. The ensuing story is as much a bildungsroman as it is an adventure tale. Tak is initially a very believable teenaged boy: though generally good-hearted, he is also reckless, impulsive, and rather spoiled. Subsequent events find him thrown into the midst of a military conspiracy, as well as theaters of war and diplomacy, which transforms his childish traits into true heroism and leadership. Accompanying Tak on his journey are his new friend Luff, a peasant boy from distant mountains, and Brieze, an intelligent and highly capable apprentice wizard.<br /><br />To be honest, I really don't read much YA, and the ones I have read were so-so at best. But this was really neat! <i>The Sailweaver's Son</i> is a fun, imaginative debut and I really look foward to more from Jeff Minerd. The only drawback I found was Brieze being the only female character (Tak's mom doesn't really do much), but she is actually the protagonist of the next book. The Kingdom of Spire is clearly a patriarchal society (the military and government are exclusively male), which is also something I would like to see explored more, especially with such a headstrong, confident girl like Brieze.<br /><br /><i>The Sailweaver's Son</i> also deals with the currently topical themes of energy dependence, xenophobia, and sabre-rattling.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8499794570722910410" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


